{
  "text": "Moreover, studies on Australian amphibian species have revealed that Bd infection is strongly associated with aquatic habitats and in frog species that hibernate in aquatic microhabitats rather than terrestrial . This pattern of aquatic amphibian species presenting higher infection and prevalence rates has also been reported among other amphibian species worldwide and has led researchers to hypothesize that terrestrial species may avoid Bd infection through microhabitat protection [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] Catenazzi et al., 2011) . Whilst Bd is more associated with aquatic habitats, terrestrial amphibians can also be infected with Bd, with some species experiencing population declines [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] Catenazzi et al., 2011) . To the best of our knowledge, only a few Australian terrestrial species have been reported with Bd infections. Negative Bd infection was reported on terrestrial Australian microhylids of the Wet Tropics [CITATION_9] . However, Bd infection was reported for Cophixalus ornatus and Assa darlingtoni Hero, 2006, 2007) . These limited and inconclusive results warrant further investigation of Bd suceptibility in Australian terrestrial amphibians, and the role of skin microbiota on host-pathogen interactions.",
